## Why most redesigns don't move the leads needle

Roughly half the redesign projects I'm asked to quote shouldn't be redesigns. The site itself isn't the problem — the SEO is, the content is thin, the conversion path is broken on one page, or the buyer profile has shifted and the messaging hasn't.

A redesign without a diagnosis ends up looking better and converting the same. Sometimes worse, because new design choices kill conversion patterns that were quietly working.

What I do instead: diagnose first, scope the fix, only redesign if redesign is the right answer.

## The diagnosis I run before quoting a redesign

Free, thirty minutes, on a discovery call. I pull up:

- **Search Console data** — impressions, clicks, position over 16 months. Where the drop happened, what fell, what's still ranking.
- **Your site** — Core Web Vitals, mobile UX, schema, indexation, conversion path on the home and main service pages.
- **Your competitors** — top three for the main service queries, what they're doing differently.
- **Analytics if available** — sessions, conversions, bounce by landing page.

By the end of the call, I can usually tell you whether you need:

- A full [website redesign](/website-design/redesign/) — visual + structural + SEO. From £2,000.
- A landing page rebuild on the existing site — cheaper, sometimes solves the leads problem alone. £600-£1,500.
- A [technical SEO audit](/services/technical-seo-audit/) and on-page fixes — no redesign needed. From £500.
- Ongoing [maintenance](/services/seo-consulting/) — the site is fine, it just needs feeding.

I'd rather lose the redesign quote and recommend the cheaper fix than sell you a redesign that doesn't work.

## Full redesign vs landing page rebuild vs ongoing maintenance

Three options at three price points:

| Scope | Best for | Approx price |
|---|---|---|
| **Full redesign** | Outdated brand, broken IA, leads dropped, platform unmaintainable | From £2,000 |
| **Landing page rebuild** | One or two pages doing the heavy lifting, conversion broken on those | £600-£1,500 |
| **UX fixes only** | Site fundamentally fine, conversion path needs tightening | £400-£800 |
| **Ongoing maintenance** | Site is fine, needs updates and small tweaks | £40/month |

Don't overspend if you don't need to. The redesign is the right answer about 50% of the time among the people who ask for one.

## UX improvements that pay back fastest

If the site doesn't need a full redesign, the highest-ROI UX changes are usually:

- **Move the phone number into the header.** Click-to-call on mobile. Single biggest mobile conversion lever for service businesses.
- **Cut contact form fields to three.** Name, phone or email, message. Anything more drops conversion.
- **State a starting price.** "From £1,500" beats "Contact for a quote" by 20-40% on enquiry rate.
- **Add a sticky CTA bar on mobile.** Scrolling visitors should always have one tap to your primary action.
- **Replace stock photography with real photos.** Even mediocre real photos outperform polished stock.
- **Tighten hero copy.** What you do, who for, where. Three to five lines max.
- **Add real testimonials with names.** Not five-star ratings. Specific outcomes.

Most of these are part of the [landing page rebuild](/website-design/landing-pages/) scope at £600-£1,500. Some are ten-minute changes you can make in WordPress without me.

## Landing page design for paid traffic and campaigns

Standalone landing pages — for Google Ads, Facebook campaigns, LinkedIn, email — need different design logic from organic-traffic pages.

What works:

- Single conversion goal per page (don't compete CTAs)
- Match between ad copy and page hero (otherwise quality score drops)
- Above-the-fold form with three fields
- Social proof in the first scroll
- FAQ section addressing the buyer's actual objections
- No header navigation (or muted) so visitors don't bounce sideways
- Schema for Service or Offer

Landing page builds typically £400-£800 each, depending on length. I'll usually do them in batches of three to five so the design system is consistent.

## Maintenance packages — when to choose them over a rebuild

If the site is structurally fine — good platform, good UX, ranking somewhat — you may not need a redesign. You may need ongoing care.

The £40/month maintenance bundle covers:

- Plugin updates (security and feature)
- WordPress core updates
- Backup verification
- Uptime monitoring
- Security scanning
- Ten minutes/month of small content tweaks

The £600/month [SEO retainer](/services/seo-consulting/) covers maintenance plus growth work — content briefs, on-page optimisation, ranking reports, monthly strategy calls.

## Aatma — a real conversion-led redesign

Healthcare clinic, existing WordPress site, leads stagnant despite local search demand. Diagnosis showed:

- Local SEO architecture absent (no service area pages, weak GBP)
- Service pages were thin — under 400 words each
- No schema beyond default Yoast Article
- Phone number buried in the contact page footer
- Mobile conversion path broken

The redesign:

- Rebuilt with proper service architecture (each treatment got a proper page)
- Schema added — MedicalBusiness, MedicalProcedure, Physician, FAQPage
- GBP rebuilt and citations submitted
- Phone moved to header with click-to-call
- Real treatment photography replaced stock

Outcomes within five months: local pack visibility for the main treatment queries, organic traffic up year-on-year, enquiries up. Full numbers and methodology in the [case study](/website-design/case-studies/).

